# Recorded Decisions
#
# WHERE THIS LIVES
# NOT in your repo. `/expert-review` writes and reads this file at a repo-keyed path OUTSIDE the
# working tree ‚Äî `~/.claude/reviews/{owner-repo}/decisions.yaml` (the key comes from the repo's
# identity, e.g. `gh repo view --json nameWithOwner`). It is deliberately untracked and un-committed.
#
# Why outside the repo: a decision suppresses reviewer findings. If this file lived in the tree, a
# branch could add an entry that silences the review OF THAT SAME BRANCH ‚Äî a change licensing itself.
# Keeping it out of every diff closes that hole structurally: the panel reads the decisions that were
# settled BEFORE the change under review, never ones the change smuggled in. Copy this template to
# that path (or let `/expert-review` create it on first ruling); edit it by hand any time.
#
# WHAT THIS IS
# The rulings you made during `/expert-review` triage, written down so the panel stops asking
# you the same question every run. Reviewers read this file at Pass 1 (see the "Load Project
# Context" step in prompts/expert-framework.md), which means a decision recorded here makes the
# NEXT review shorter. That is the whole point: the report shrinks as the project's judgment
# accumulates.
#
# `/expert-review` appends to this file, but only with your approval, and only after proposing
# the exact wording.
#
# THE BAR ‚Äî patterns only
# Record the pattern and the SPIRIT behind it, not the instance that provoked it.
# If it wouldn't survive being explained to a new engineer as "how we think here," it does not
# belong in this file.
#
#   YES  "Errors cross a module boundary as typed values, never as exceptions ‚Äî callers should
#          not need to read our source to know what can go wrong."
#   NO   "Use `const` on line 42 of auth.ts."
#   NO   "Prefer `map` over `for` loops."          (taste, not a decision)
#   YES  "We accept unbounded memory in the batch importer; it runs offline against a bounded
#          input, and the complexity of streaming isn't worth it until that stops being true."
#
# A file full of nits is WORSE than an empty one. Reviewers treat these as settled law and will
# stop raising real findings that brush against them. Keep it short. Prune it.
#
# EVERY ENTRY HERE IS LIVE. To overturn a decision, EDIT or DELETE the entry in place ‚Äî never
# append a replacement beside it. There is no `supersedes` field: history lives in git (of this
# file's own directory) and in the ledger, not in the file's live rows. Two entries that disagree
# is a bug, because a reviewer cannot tell which one binds.
#
# WHAT A DECISION CANNOT DO
# A recorded decision DEMOTES; it never DELETES. It can lower a finding's priority or mark it
# accepted, but it can never suppress a CRITICAL, and never suppress a finding in the security
# domain. Those still surface, annotated with the decision that covers them. `project.yaml`
# `invariants` and `redLines` also outrank anything here.
#
# When a decision changes how the system is SHAPED rather than how it is written, it is an ADR,
# not an entry here. Triage will tell you when it thinks it's crossed that line.

decisions:
  - name: <the pattern, in a few words ‚Äî not the instance>   # required

    rule: >          # required
      What we do, stated as a pattern that generalizes beyond the finding that provoked it.

    spirit: >        # required ‚Äî load-bearing
      WHY. The intent behind the rule ‚Äî the thing that lets a reader apply it to a case you
      never anticipated, and recognize when it does NOT apply. A rule without its spirit gets
      cargo-culted into places it was never meant to go, and then someone deletes it because it
      produced a stupid result. An entry missing `spirit` is not settled law ‚Äî a reviewer treats
      it as advisory and flags normally.

    appliesTo: >     # required ‚Äî the HARD boundary
      Where this holds ‚Äî and, just as importantly, where it does not. This is the outer wall:
      OUTSIDE it the decision is silent, full stop. Inside it, `spirit` decides whether it actually
      reaches the case in front of the reviewer. An entry missing `appliesTo` is not settled law ‚Äî
      it is treated as advisory, never as universally scoped. Scope keeps a good decision from
      metastasizing into a bad one.

    revisitIf: >     # optional ‚Äî the staleness trigger
      The condition under which this decision stops being true (e.g. "the importer starts taking
      untrusted input"). When a reviewer sees the diff make this condition hold, the decision no
      longer binds ‚Äî flag the finding, cite this entry by name, and say what changed.

    source: review <REVIEW_DIR basename>, YYYY-MM-DD   # provenance ‚Äî where this ruling came from
